### PHP Variable Scope

Scope refers to the visibility and accessibility of variables in different parts of a PHP script.

### Local Scope

Variables declared inside a function are local to that function.

```php
<?php
function test() {
    $localVar = "I am local";
    echo $localVar; // Works
}

test();
echo $localVar; // Error: undefined
?>
```

### Global Scope

Variables declared outside functions have global scope.

```php
<?php
$globalVar = "I am global";

function test() {
    // Cannot access $globalVar here
    echo $globalVar; // Warning: undefined
}
?>
```

### Accessing Global Variables

```php
<?php
$name = "John";

function greet() {
    global $name; // Declare as global
    echo "Hello, $name";
}

greet(); // Hello, John

// Alternative: $GLOBALS array
function greet2() {
    echo "Hello, " . $GLOBALS['name'];
}
?>
```

### Scope Summary

| Scope | Defined In | Accessible |
|-------|-----------|------------|
| Global | Outside functions | Everywhere except inside functions (unless `global`) |
| Local | Inside functions | Only within that function |
| Static | Inside functions | Only within that function (but persists between calls) |
| Superglobal | PHP built-in | Everywhere |

> **Key Point:** Variables defined in the global scope are NOT accessible inside functions by default. Use the `global` keyword or `$GLOBALS` array.
